shared_text:
Food Gatherers
September 2 at 1:43 PM ·

On Saturday, we partnered with the Washtenaw County Office of Community & Economic Development, Ypsilanti Community Schools, and Metro by T-Mobile to make sure families have everything they need to get their kids ready for school. We helped give out around 900 backpacks, 500 grocery boxes, as well as hundreds of hot meals, and thousands of hand sanitizers and disinfecting wipes!

A huge thank you to our partners at Metro by T-Mobile, who sponsored the grocery boxes. Thanks to their support, families received boxes full of kid-friendly snack and lunch options, plus fun activity sheets!

Going back to school may look different this year but together with our community partners and sponsors, we are making sure our kids have everything they need to learn and grow! #WorkingTogether #FightingHunger #washtenawcounty

Ypsi Mask Project Launched To Help Ypsilanti Community Schools

A group of Ypsilanti residents launched a program called the Ypsi Mask Project for the purpose of making masks for Ypsilanti Community Schools.

The goal is to provide masks to students, teachers and staff who will be taking part in face-to-face instruction in the fall. The Ypsi Mask Project has teamed up with Engage @ EMU to make 4,000 masks. Maria Goodrich co-founded the Ypsi Mask Project in July and says, so far, they’ve made about 900 masks for Ypsilanti Community Schools.

Click on link below to listen to the story.
https://www.wemu.org/post/ypsi-mask-project-launched-help-ypsilanti-community-schools

post_text:
Parkridge Summerfest/Joe Dulin Community Day

Parkridge SummerFest/Joe Dulin Community Day is going virtual this year! It is going to be a two-part event, with the first happening today at 2pm. It will be a Facebook Livestream of various musical performances and community presentations from the school system, the health department, and other community organizations. You can join at the following link: www.facebook.com/events/304437393978503

The second part of the event will happen next week at the same time – Saturday, August 29th at 2pm. It will be a large, physically distanced school supply and grocery drive-thru where we hope to give out filled backpacks and packs of groceries to hundreds, if not thousands of area students. This location of this event is still being finalized; we will let you know as soon as it is. If you are interested in volunteering at the drive-thru next week, we would love your help! Please email lindemanp@washtenaw.org if you are interested.

post_text:
Ypsi Community Schools return with three different educational models tailored to students' needs
While the 2020-2021 school year will look different for children across the country, Ypsilanti Community Schools (YCS) will offer three different instruction models to fit parents' and students' varying needs and safety concerns.

YCS Superintendent Alena Zachery-Ross notes that while the entire district only has about 600 staff members, nearly 100 volunteered to be on the district's back-to-school safety task force, which started in May. That group has considered guidelines from the CDC, Gov. Gretchen Whitmer's school reopening safety plan, and what other districts are planning. Zachery-Ross also drew feedback from a parent advisory council.

Link to article
https://www.secondwavemedia.com/concentrate/features/ycsbacktoschool0560.aspx
#YCSDynamic

shared_text:
Packard Health
August 11 at 9:45 AM ·

Agricultural Worker Health Day

Packard Health encourages its patients to prioritize their health and wellness. This includes consuming healthy, fresh foods. Our staff, including our on-site dietitian and patient advocates, connect patients to the abundance of area farmers markets. Qualified patients are referred to the "Prescription for Health" program (a partnership with the Washtenaw County Health Department) so they can receive $100 to spend at local farmers markets. This allows patients to buy local - in turn, supporting local agricultural workers, their families, livelihood, and health, too!

post_text:
EMU Today
Office of Engage @ EMU launches Child Development Certificate Pipeline Pilot Program
Program will offer financial assistance to those who would like to receive their certificate in child development in order to work in Washtenaw County child development centers
YPSILANTI – The Office of Engage@EMU is responding to a critical need for child development employees in eastern Washtenaw County by providing an entryway into employment as an assistant or lead teacher at a child development center site.

This Child Development Certificate (CDC) Pipeline Program enables community members to take their CDC courses at Washtenaw Community College (WCC) while completing their practicum semester at The Collaborative: Ypsilanti YMCA Child Development Center.

Link to complete press release
https://today.emich.edu/story/news/11464

Please join us tonight, Wednesday, August 5th starting at 6 P.M., for part two of our YCS Virtual Town Hall Meeting! We have a special presentation from the Washtenaw County Health Department to give an update on the pandemic and its effects on schools.

We will also go over several important topics about the upcoming 2020-2021 school year! The event will be live on Facebook and Zoom. Links to the Zoom login and Facebook Live are below:

Parent Return to School Survey

The 2020-21 school year is fast approaching, and the district is seeking input from parents/guardians with a return-to-school survey.

School closures due to the Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) this spring forced public school systems to rethink instructional learning models, stakeholder communication, and strategic plans.

To plan for reopening in a pandemic, we are seeking input from our district parents/guardians as you are important collaborators in the decision-making process.

Please complete the survey before July 24, 2020.

Good Morning:

Our beloved Henry Ford Early Learning Center caught fire yesterday evening, and the cause of the fire is under investigation.

The Board of Education, district administrators, and the Henry Ford family are incredibly grateful no one was injured and that the Superior Township Fire Department was quickly on the scene to help control the situation.

Henry Ford has been a staple in the Willow Run Community for many years, and we will work hard to get the building in a safe condition before the start of the new school year.

We Are YCS

post_text:
Ypsilanti Community Schools Presents...

K-12 Online Summer Learning Program - A Project-Based Student-Directed Learning Experience
Program Description

YCS is offering an alternative robust K-12 Online Summer Learning Program that allows all of our students to continue to learn throughout the Summer by participating in a project-based learning experience that is highly engaging, meant to be fun, and is totally student self-directed. The K-12 Online Summer Learning Program consists of having our students actively participate in the following academic experiences:

All YCS participating students will be engaged in an independent self-directed Living History Project where they will create their personal stories.

Students will participate in a 100 Book Challenge.
Students will also be able to spend 20 minutes three times per week on Imagine Math and 20 minutes three times per week on Imagine Literacy/Reading.

Drive-Thru spectators (families and friends) will only be permitted in the Shadford Field parking lot for picture opportunities.

Rutherford Pool
June 10 at 10:25 PM ·

After much discussion the Friends of the Rutherford Pool Board has made the difficult decision not to open the pool for the rest of the season. We know many of you are disappointed, we are too! But we feel this is in the best interest of the safety and health of our community. Below are some of the reasons we've made this decision:
We are concerned that it would be impossible to maintain social distancing while guests are in the pool.

We would have to limit guest capacity which would mean some people would be turned away at the door.

With construction of the bathhouse still not complete we would only open at most half the season. This would cause us to likely lose significant revenue.

Most importantly, we do not want to put our staff and guests at any risk to catch or spread the virus.

We are hopeful that we can take this summer to complete construction and be ready for an awesome season in 2021. Until then, please stay safe and keep in touch with all your pool staff. We miss you!

Ypsilanti Community Schools takes all claims of sexual assault or misconduct very seriously and is committed to providing safe environments for everyone in our YCS community. We understand that there are allegations of a person who has had previous ties with Ypsilanti Community Schools on the #EMUExpose page. We encourage anyone that is a victim of sexual assault or misconduct to contact a local police authority and file an incident report.

All staff who work in the district go through a screening process with the Washtenaw County Sheriff’s Office (LiveScan) and/or through the Washtenaw Intermediate School District. Any volunteers who interact with our students or programs are screened using the Internet Criminal History Access Tool (Ichat).

Again, Ypsilanti Community Schools is committed to providing safe environments for all of our students and support our community stakeholders who may need to report an incident.

post_text:
Good Evening YCS Staff, Families, and Community-

The YCS Food Distribution Program will continue at the ten locations on Thursday's in the Ypsilanti area until June 25. Once food distribution is over on June 25, the district will transition to the Meet Up Eat Up food program beginning July 1. More information on locations will be communicated soon on program logistics.

We are excited to announce a new program that will be available to families starting Tuesday, May 26, that will provide 200 families weekly fresh produce boxes. This program is called the Heeren USDA Farmers to Family Food Box program. The distribution of the produce boxes will occur every Tuesday from 12-2 pm on a first-come, first-serve basis at the Old Willow Run Middle School. To maintain social distancing regulations, distribution will be done with patrons staying in their vehicles.

If you are interested in volunteering for our food programs, please contact Jerilyn Lynn via email at jlynn6@yschools.us.

Thank you, and have a great evening and week!

When asked to log in from the link above, members of the public should pick a two-digit number between 00 and 99, and log in using one of the accounts created for this purpose:

Anyone from the public can register their attendance at the following link. If they would like to ask a question or make a public comment to the board, there is a place for that, as well:

PLEASE READ THE DOCUMENTS ATTACHED IN DETAIL TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT ADDITIONAL PICKUP DAYS!

YCS Technology Distribution is CLOSED for the day due to the number of cars and safety issues. It is very likely the Washtenaw County Sheriff's Department will turn you away if you are trying to enter.

Currently, there is a wait time of 2+ hours. We apologize for the inconvenience, but again, we are working under the state restrictions, and volunteers are doing the best they can! We all received a lot of parents that came on a day not assigned, which also holds up the process.

Please review the calendar for your day of distribution for your child. If you have multiple children, you should come next week Tuesday and Wednesday--not today or this week!

Good Evening YCS Community:

Due to the recent emergency closure of our schools, businesses, and the community, we know it is a great time to clean out your house. However, we ask that you do not illegally dump your trash in YCS school dumpsters or on our property! Due to the school buildings being closed, we have reduced trash pickups, and illegal dumping costs the school district money!

Signs will now be posted on dumpsters reminding the community that school buildings will be monitored closely moving forward, and those that illegally dump will be reported.

Please help us keep our school properties clean while our buildings are closed, and we are online learning! We are one community--Stronger Together!

Thank you and please share!

shared_text:
Washtenaw County Health Department
April 6 at 2:40 PM ·

We’ve gotten questions about what “Stay Home. Stay Safe. Save Lives.” really means. It means avoiding ALL gatherings – don’t hang out with even just one or two people who aren't your household members. Go out only for essentials like food or medicine. If you need medical care, call first. If out, wear a cloth covering over your nose and mouth and keep a distance of 6 feet from others. Wash your hands well and often. If you have any symptoms (cough, shortness of breath, sore throat, diarrhea, fever), stay in a separate room from others in your home. Everyone is at risk for coronavirus and should continue taking every precaution to help slow the spread of illness. We’re in this together. All of these actions will save lives.

Find the most up-to-date information on our website www.washtenaw.org/COVID19. For tips and resources for taking care of your emotional health during these stressful times, see www.washtenaw.org/3114/Mental-Health

#StayHomeWashtenaw

Thank you for your continued support as we work through this emergency closure.

Good Afternoon YCS Community:

Due to the COVID-19 Advisory, there are restrictions on the usage of some outside district areas. The following areas will be restricted or closed until further notice:

~YCHS Tennis Courts are closed until further notice.

~All YCS Playgrounds are closed until further notice.

~YCHS Baseball and Softball Fields are closed until further notice. Visitors may use the field to walk or jog around the area with social distancing guidelines of six feet or more implemented unless within the same family.

~YCHS Track is open with social distancing guidelines of six feet or more implemented unless within the same family.

Our goal in implementing these restrictions is to keep our community safe and healthy.

Thank you

Ypsilanti Community Schools would like to thank everyone who has participated in the planning of the F.A.C.E. Conference and your willingness to be present on Saturday, March 14, 2020. Due to the recommendation of the Governor of Michigan and the Washtenaw County Health Department regarding Novel Coronavirus COVID-19 and large gatherings of more than 100 people, we have decided to cancel this event.

Please look forward to future communications regarding a new date.

Again, thank you for your support of Ypsilanti Community Schools.

post_text:
Tomorrow is Voting Day!

Michigan residents that have a past criminal record, including a felony, probation, or parole CAN VOTE!

If a person is currently incarcerated, they can not vote until released.

Michigan residents may also register to vote on the day of voting! Please visit gotv.site for more information.

Senator Jeff Irwin provided this information at the Parkridge Community Center meeting today!

***One point of clarification on the right to vote that came from Washtenaw ISD--If someone is incarcerated but not yet sentenced, they CAN vote. Only once they are sentenced do they lose that right. There are programs internally that will support their right to vote.

future, and our voice in government. Learn

This summer, the Washtenaw County Parks and Recreation Commission is pleased to offer Sumer Playground Camp at: Superior Township at Christian Love Church, West Willow at New Covenant Church, and Sugar brook Neighborhood at Grace Fellowship Church. Kids will enjoy arts and crafts, group games, interactive nature fun, weekly themes, and more! The camp is available for children who have completed kindergarten to 11 years old. Camp begins June 22nd - August 13th from 9:00 am to 4:00 pm.

If you know someone interested in attending, be sure to register March 1, 2020 because space is limited. For more information, please contact Karen Lewis at (734) 971-6337 x.324 or lewisk2@washtenaw.org
